      <h2>Why Harmonium is Ideal for Home Learning</h2>
      <p>The harmonium is one of the most learner-friendly instruments in Indian music. Unlike sitar or tabla, harmonium produces clean predictable pitches at the press of a key — there is no complex bowing or striking technique to master before you can make musical sounds. In India harmonium is everywhere: temples, kirtan groups, classical concerts, Bollywood studios, and family drawing rooms. Learning it gives you immediate access to an enormous repertoire.</p>

      <h2>What You Need</h2>
      <p>You need either a physical harmonium or our free web harmonium. For your first few weeks we strongly recommend our online web harmonium at harmoniumhalt.com/practice — this lets you learn swaras, alankars, and basic songs without any financial investment. When ready to buy a physical harmonium expect to spend Rs 5000 to Rs 15000 for a good beginner instrument. Brands like Bina, Paloma, and Sur are reliable choices.</p>

      <h2>Your 3-Month Roadmap</h2>
      <p>Month 1: Learn all 7 swaras (Sa Re Ga Ma Pa Dha Ni), start Alankars 1-4, establish daily 20-minute practice habit. Month 2: Learn Alankars 5-10, master your first bhajan (Raghupati Raghav), begin one raga's aroha-avaroha. Month 3: Complete your first raga (Yaman), add 2 more bhajans to repertoire, begin simple improvisation within Yaman.</p>

      <h2>Daily Practice Structure</h2>
      <p>Consistency beats intensity. 20-30 focused minutes daily produces better results than 2 hours on weekends. Structure: Minutes 0-5 slow scale warm-up, Minutes 5-15 alankar practice, Minutes 15-25 current song or lesson material, Minutes 25-30 free creative playing. This structure covers all aspects of harmonium development systematically.</p>

      <h2>Common Beginner Mistakes</h2>
      <p>Rushing through basics without proper foundation. Practicing too fast before patterns are precise. Skipping alankars because they seem boring. Not singing swara names while playing. Using poor posture that causes wrist strain. Learning too many songs at once instead of mastering one at a time. Each of these mistakes significantly slows progress — avoiding them from the start is crucial.</p>

